Step 4: Best Practices for Creating Strong Passwords
1.	Use at least 12â€“16 characters.
2.	Include uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols.
3.	Avoid dictionary words, names, or obvious patterns.
4.	Use passphrases (e.g., â€œT!gerRunsFast2025!â€).
5.	Do not reuse passwords across accounts.
Step 5: Tips Learned from Evaluation
â€¢	Short and simple passwords are easily broken.
â€¢	Adding numbers and symbols dramatically increases strength.
â€¢	Length matters: longer passwords are much harder to crack.
â€¢	Randomness > predictable substitutions (e.g., Pa$$w0rd is still weak).
Step 6: Common Password Attacks
â€¢	Brute Force Attack: Tries every possible combination until it finds the password (short/simple ones fall quickly).
â€¢	Dictionary Attack: Uses common words or leaked password lists.
â€¢	Hybrid Attack: Combines dictionary words with variations (like Password123).
Step 7: How Password Complexity Affects Security
â€¢	Passwords with only lowercase letters are very weak and can be cracked within seconds.
â€¢	Adding numbers, uppercase, and symbols increases the time needed for cracking.
â€¢	Longer, more complex passwords (especially random passphrases) can take years or centuries to crack with brute force.
 Conclusion:
Password strength depends mainly on length, complexity, and unpredictability. A good practice is to use long passphrases with a mix of characters, and never reuse passwords across accounts.
